AI Meeting Knowledge System – Problem & Solution Architecture

1. Problem Statement
Organizations conduct numerous meetings every day. Important decisions, action items, and discussions are often buried inside long recordings or meeting notes. Teams struggle to quickly retrieve key information from past meetings, resulting in lost knowledge, repeated discussions, and reduced productivity.
The challenge is to build a scalable system that can process meeting recordings, convert speech to text, analyze the conversation, and automatically extract useful insights such as summaries, decisions, and action items.

2. Objectives

• Automatically process meeting recordings and generate transcripts.
• Extract key insights such as decisions, tasks, and summaries.
• Provide a searchable interface for users to find information quickly.
• Support scalability for large numbers of meetings.
• Ensure high performance and reliability.

3. High-Level Solution Overview
The proposed solution is a scalable architecture that uses asynchronous processing, distributed services, and caching mechanisms to efficiently process and retrieve meeting insights.
The system allows users to upload meeting audio recordings through a web interface. The recordings are stored in object storage, and processing tasks are sent to a message queue for asynchronous execution. Worker services process the recordings, perform speech-to-text conversion, and extract insights using NLP models.



4. Key Architecture Components

• Load Balancer
Distributes incoming traffic across multiple API instances to ensure high availability and improved performance.
• API Gateway / Backend Services
Acts as the central entry point for all requests. Handles authentication, routing, and communication with backend services.
• Message Queue (RabbitMQ)
Enables asynchronous processing by sending heavy tasks such as transcription and NLP analysis to worker services.
• Worker Services
Background workers consume tasks from the queue and perform speech-to-text transcription, NLP processing, and action item extraction.
• Database Layer
A relational database stores transcripts, meeting metadata, extracted decisions, and action items.
• Cache Layer (Redis)
Redis is used as a distributed cache to store frequently accessed data and reduce database load.
• Object Storage
Stores uploaded meeting recordings using scalable storage such as cloud blob storage.

5. Scalability Considerations
The system is designed to scale horizontally. Additional API instances can be added behind the load balancer to handle increased traffic. Worker services can scale independently based on the number of messages in the queue. Redis caching helps reduce database load and improve response times.


6. Trade-Offs
Using asynchronous processing with a message queue improves system responsiveness and scalability but introduces additional infrastructure complexity.
Using Redis caching improves performance but requires careful cache invalidation strategies to maintain data consistency.

7. Benefits of the Proposed Architecture
• Improved performance through caching and asynchronous processing.
• High scalability using distributed workers and load balancing.
• Better reliability and fault tolerance.
• Faster retrieval of meeting insights for end users.




